&lt;p&gt;
	&lt;strong&gt;First Window:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;
		&lt;strong&gt;Build the Warchest:&lt;/strong&gt; Since there&amp;#39;s no free agents in Year 1, transfer fees must be paid. Raise funds for needed talent by selling as many non-starting players as possible.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;
		&lt;strong&gt;Shelf Life: &lt;/strong&gt;Always buy as young as possible, even when it&amp;#39;s at a premium. Chances are the talent is underevaluated. Coming back from the offseason, you&amp;#39;ll notice they&amp;#39;ve gained 2-3 points Overall as well. Look through major and second-tier leagues for World-Class youth talent (age 17-21) that already has a rating of 78+. These players will be monsters in a few years and can be locked into lower wages on long contracts.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;
		&lt;strong&gt;Single-Year Commitment: &lt;/strong&gt;Negotiate player signings with 1-year contracts. Once they&amp;#39;re on the roster, they&amp;#39;ll often take a pay cut (up to 50%) for an extra year extension. If they won&amp;#39;t re-up for another year with a pay cut or equal salary, they&amp;#39;re a long term headache and you should put them back up for sale.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;
		&lt;strong&gt;Shopping List:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
		- World Class keeper under age of 22&lt;br /&gt;
		- World-Class utility midfielder under age of 22&lt;br /&gt;
		- World-Class CB under age of 22&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
